      "@type": "Project",
      "schema:legalName": "ORCA Line Transect Distance Sampling",
      "schema:name": "ORCA Line Transect Distance Sampling",
      "schema:url": "https://www.orcaweb.org.uk/",
      "schema:description": "With our unique take on marine conservation, ORCA is a charity that’s entirely dedicated to studying and protecting whales, dolphins and porpoises in UK and European waters. We work to identify and protect critical whale and dolphin habitats in our waters and beyond. Thanks to the generosity of our supporters we help to create safer places for whales and dolphins ultimately promoting the health of our seas.\r\nORCA is passionate about people; in fact our work is as much about people as it is about whales and dolphins. What makes ORCA unique is our dedication to combining accessible marine education with our conservation activities allowing us to give ordinary people opportunities to take an active role in marine science and conservation. The identification of important whale and dolphin habitats is carried out by ORCA’s Marine Mammal Survey Teams, who are all volunteers. This is what makes us so unique. It’s our own volunteer teams on board ferries and cruise ships in European waters that conduct the monthly scientific surveys, recording the species we see, where they are and what they’re doing. They run talks for passengers and activities on deck, providing expert knowledge of the astonishing marine wildlife on our doorstep.\r\nThe line transect distance sampling data is collected from the bridge of ferries. A team of highly trained observers record cetacean sightings according to standard line-transect distance sampling methods from a platform of opportunity, typically a ferry or cruise ship. Effort information including vessel location, speed, course of vessel and environmental conditions, such as sea state and visibility, are recorded every 30 minutes when observers rotate positions or when conditions change. When a sighting is made, the location of the ship, the angle and distance to the sighting and other relevant information including species, group size, number of calves and behaviour is recorded.",
